text:
All fantastic BBQ places, but I put Franklin's in place of Snow's. I didn't enjoy Snow's brisket as much as I enjoyed Tootsie's chicken. The chicken could become an addiction. Also, LeRoy & Lewis brisket was good but didn't wow me. The flat iron and beef cheeks are outstanding,  as are the sides. And the L&L burger is winner. Of course it's just person's opinion. 

If I had to choose one BBQ place in Austin for the experience as a whole, meaning no long lines, good bbq, atmosphere, and service, I would choose Terry Black's.

text:
Born and raised in Houston and now living in central Texas... I. F**king. Love. Brisket.
Its just one of the best things ever to me. Even a "bad" brisket is pretty good, but when you get that GOOD brisket, oh my loooord. 

Absolutely loved the video. The criteria for the brisket itself is perfect imo. It's pretty much exactly how I judge places. Good seasoning, texture and tenderness, fat level and rendering, and overall juicyness. Love a nice crust, and a good amount of smoke but not overwhelming.

I'm pretty much smack dab in the middle of Austin and Dallas so I'm absolutely gonna visit some of these places.
If anyone has any recommendations for the Waco/Temple/Killeen area I would love to know. I haven't found anything better than decent around here.

text: Joshua... The BEST BBQ Sauce you'll ever eat is 3 simple ingredients...  In a 1 cup Pyrex measuring cup put in 1 T of Soy Sauce 1/3 cup of Worcestershire Sauce and fill the rest of the cup with Light Brown Sugar to fill to 1 cup ...stir good then heat in a microwave for 1 min 50 sec to 2 mins but watch the boiling so it doesnt over flow the cup... When done stir good again and heat in microwave again for less than 2 mins and watch so it doesnt boil over... When dont place cup in fridge for 3-4 hours so its thick thick that a spoon stand up in the sauce... Now heres the thing, you have to cook your meat like ribs, london broil over charcoal brickets ONLY ... It doesnt work on a gas grill at all... Baste your meat on both sides and cook... But make sure you baste your meat before flipping it... Baste your meat at least 4 times on both sides so it caramelizes THICKLY ... Its the best sauce you'll ever eat in your life
author: @moviesclassics1970

text:
I have a potato salad recipe which is the best in the world 


Ingredients 
Potatoes  1-2 Potatoes per person
Eggs for a big batch I usually use around 12
Bacon - at least 1 pound
Pickles  dill or dill relish
Onion 1 medium
Celery -6-9 stalks depending on how many Potatoes you use 
Salt 
Peper
Garlic
Paprika- smoked if you have it
Mayonaise 
Mustard

Skin potatoes- dice them into cubes less than an inch big- put them on to boil.  Stop them before mashed potato soft.  Drain them and place them in a spot to cool.

Dice Bacon and fry it crisp drain and set aside 

Hard boil your eggs then peel and chop

Finely dice/mince your onion

Dice celery- i tend to dice them pretty fine

If you are using pickle chips or any thing other than relish go ahead and dice it as well.

Combine all of these ingredients into a large bowl,  

Add mayonaise i usually start with 2-3 cups 
Add a real health squit of mustard probably 3-4 tablespoons at least 

Salt, pepper, garlic, even some Tony's if you got it.  I have never measured it.  Im guessing i woukd be at a minimum of tablespoon of each.  Maybe less for the Tony's until you taste it.

Fold it all together well. Trying to avoid mashing all of your Potatoes.   Some mashing is good but we want to still have some chunks. 

Youll have to look at it and taste it now.  Did we get enough mayonaise.  It shoukd be creamy not dry, but not soupy. 

Then taste for seasoning.  Does it taste like you remember it.  If not add a little more seasoning until it tastes like you want it to.

Sometimes if its a little dry or before I get to much mayonaise in it, I will put a bit of pickle juice in.

Once it is how I like it.  I will smooth it all out in the bowl and spr8nkle the top red with the paprika.   It is optional but I think it adds something,  if nothing it is nostalgia from my youth!

text: My family is from the Lockhart/Luling area, for almost 200 years now. The key for great Brisket is the right wood Post Oak and Pecan, low and slow heat, and meat with marbling and a decent fat cap.  You don't need anything else, but patience and maybe a thermometer. Getting the right temp, holding it, pulling the meat off and letting it rest will take you off over the finish line.

text: Loved the video! Loved the idea, the road trip aspect, just all around good format. I would also recommend this for a Louisiana based video. . we have 3 regions in the state. . . text: Some people making fun about Josh criticising about salt. I'm making a living by cooking, and I believe salt is the most important in flavor. When you measure everything up, cook it up the right way, but in the end, the flavor still off. At that point, either it is too salty or you need more salt. I cook large batch for 800-1000 serving per day, you can prepare the ingredients & condiments well but most of the time, you still need to adjust for salt

4 Rivers could probably hold its wait for the most part only because I'm pretty sure that the founder of Four Rivers is actually from Texas and he's actually bringing Texas style barbecue outside of the state..

I think Four Rivers actually shines more in their sides than their actual brisket because Four Rivers has been hit or miss and not consistent with their brisket. 

If you're in Florida and you know if you're near one you should try Mission BBQ I think they are better overall than four rivers for barbecue and maybe the sides aren't as good as for Rivers but they are pretty close but Sonny's BBQ is really chain garbage for a lot of people but they have some decent things

text:
@buzztrucker  I know it's probably garbage compared to Texas, but that frame is reference is really useful for those that don't have the luxury to travel just to try some of these places out. A rating system without a scale or control is kind of pointless because there's a lot of people that haven't eaten a single one of these restaurants. 

Also these cooks know Josh is visiting because he likes to talk with owners and staff and film B roll and they may give him special treatment so his experience might be different from the average experience someone else may get. These videos are fun but I think Josh should make a bit more effort to minimize bias and give people a frame of reference for these ratings.

text: First time i went to snows was back in 2016 and it was the best bbq I ever had. I did wait about 2 hours in line to place our order and we got there an hour before they before they opened.  Their smoked chickens are amazing. The brisket changed the way I saw bbq. I tried going there in 2023 and the place blew up. We would have had to wait about half a day to get our brisket and ended up taking an L and left. I know this is silly, but I cried on the way back to the place we were staying at. Just really hit me unexpectedly. What a pivotal memory it was and how that little bbq place no one knew about was now a well known place with a netflix show. I didn't know about the netflix show till after we had driven out there. I was just a bit heartbroken I couldn't share this place with my partner due to the heat and just how long we would have had to have waited. I'm sorry but it wasn't worth spending 10 hours for food.
author: @annekagrif

text: I was in Richardson TX, outside of Dallas a few years back. Ordered some doordash from the closest BBQ from my hotel which was called Ten50 BBQ. Was by far the best brisket I've ever had from a BBQ place, and I just chose it at random because it was close. I'm from the KC area, and they do a lot of things right, but brisket is rarely that great here. It's always sliced thin and lacks flavor, which leads to drying out. Texas at least seems to render it correctly and slices it thick so it stays crazy tender. Goes a long way. I like the flavor profiles of pretty much all BBQ capitals though.

text:
I was kidnapped, and brought here as an 8 year old. I will not bore you further with that, but I will tell you that my mother’s people go back 178 years. I have been force-fed “texas bbq” since I was 8 years old (I am staring down the barrel of my 60’s, but still in the middle), and I still prefer a Santa Maria, and a good Tri Tip. My grandfather used to make smokers out of discarded oil barrels. He gave them to all of his sons, and none of his daughters. None of my uncles made delicious bbq. I recall a lot of burned, dry yuk…but then again, they were blackout drunks.
That said, I get it. I do enjoy excellent texas bbq, but it is hard to find. I do not care for mediocrity in this, above many things.

text: As a native Texan who has lived all over the state, Austin and the Hill Country, no doubt, have the most badass barbecue places than anyplace else in the state, hands down. Sure, there are some good places sprinkled around the Houston, Dallas, and South Texas areas, but there are a lot more mediocre places in those places than not. That isn't the case in and around Austin, where most of the places are exceptional. We moved from Austin to Conroe in 2013 and really miss the barbecue in Austin, Lockhart, Luling, etc. Out here there's Corkscrew, which is exceptional but overpriced. There is Truth, which is in Houston, but who wants to go to Houston? There is one place in Montgomery, Texas called Jennings and Company, which is a little food truck next to a meat market only open on weekends that is my favorite within a hundred mile radius. They really do it right.

text: I've lived in Texas my whole life, we did a Texas BBQ tour for a friend's bachelor party. Let me tell y'all the secret for anyone outside of Texas - almost 100% of your experience is directly dependent on the time you arrive. The food - it's all the same. There's a point in history that you just can't get any better - we're there. It is true that some will be slightly better than others, but the drive to some of these places does not justify the difference. The BIGGEST factor in ALL of Texas BBQ places is the time that you arrive at the location. I can't tell you how many times I walked into a famous location right after a rush, and hated it. Only to come back later in the year right before a rush and have it completely blow me away. All of these vidoes of youtubers doing Texas BBQ places don't ever show them coming back after 3 or 4 months. THAT's the true test. And just about any famous place that you can Google holds up. Since I live closest to Hutchin's - that's where I'll go.
author: @flatfeetlefthanded

text:
Texas Method of Smoking Briskets
Apply a 50/50 mix of Course Salt and Black Pepper . 
Get the Smoker Temp up to 225-250 degrees F and place the Brisket FAT CAP Up with the point towards the fire source and the flat away from the fire source. Smoke cook at 225 to 250 degrees for 4-5 hours. 
Remove when it stalls at 165 degrees F and double wrap it in Red or Pink Butcher paper and then place it back on the grill of the Smoker unit and insert a Meat Probe Temp gauge and continue to cook another 3-5 hours or until the Temp reaches about 210 to 225 degrees. Then remove from the smoker unit, leaving it still wrapped in the butcher paper, wrap it in an large clean bath towel and place it into the bottom of an insulated cooler chest and let it rest for about 2 hours more before unwrapping , slicing and serving. Rule of thumb is 60 to 90 minute per lb. , so a 10 lb Brisket would a cook time of at least 10 to 12 hours ! Never inject, marinade or sauce a Brisket !! AND NEVER NEVER Wrap Brisket in Aluminum Foil !!!!!!!!

text: @ well Japan use to not let their cattle leave their country because in specific regions their cattle goes through strict guidelines in order to be graded highly and keep a high demand. They have a whole process of respecting their high grade beef, like Kobe, and we just saw dollar signs! I think they ended that program.

text:
Gives me a chance to get everyone to Google Japanese vs American beef grading systems. American Prime is equivalent to Japanese A2, and there are even 5 Beef Marbling Scale (BMS) grade divisions within A5 so there's a level of silliness the marketers haven't even tapped yet.

But "wagyu" just means "Japanese Cow" and "American Wagyu" can be crossbred, and the grading is separate, so that there "American Wagyu" there may not even have been Prime grade (though it probably was given how it was objectively competitive).

text:
$18/pound for brisket at Goldees, and two slices is about 1/2 pound. A 1/2 pound side is $6. $7 for banana pudding, and $6 for a beer. So $28 per person before tax, $30 after. You can convert to ISO, I'm too hungry to do the googling...

TBH, for the quality, that's cheap. Far lesser places are charging 10-30% more and serving tough, livery brisket. Goldees is a bit out of the way though, and doesn't have downtown-location rent to pay, so it's priced to keep people making the effort.

text: "Every time a customer comes back, you wanna give 'em the exact same experience." YES! I try to drill that into to cooks, consistency is key. People tend to want the same things the same way, week after week, and if it's not the same every time they'll eat somewhere else. People will take a consistent 7/10 over a 10/10 that's sometimes a 5/10. That's why people still flock to McDonald's even though it's bad and not even cheap, because when they go there they know what they're getting.

text: This. 99% of customers choose that place that day because they got a taste in their mouth for that thing they like there. If the food is off in just the wrong way you'll break that association and the ideation won't happen organically for them as easily, and you'll slow their return rate or lose them entirely. True regulars who show up without a craving usually do like a little variation in the standards, but they can get enough variety by choosing different menu items and you shouldn't drive your customer base away for them.

NB: Black's and Terry Black's are family related but not business related. It's a whole thing. And imo Black's is better than Terry Black's.
